snippet.textDisplay: It's not the governments fault, nor is it climate change. It's the councils fault for not implementing back burning and fire breaks just to save a buck. They increase rates and don't put much back into the community. They only want to line their own pockets. Over the years I see less and less back burning. The aboriginals who lived on this land have been doing it for centuries to catch and hunt food through controlled burning before the first settlements came. Some fires were used to populate and encourage native seed germination in the Australian bush land. At the end of the day when you burn all the fuel, there is nothing left to burn.

snippet.textDisplay: Living on the South Coast of New South Wales I can tell you that we haven’t seen blue sky or stars at night in months. Every day the skies are grey or even brown. These fires have been a mix of reasons. At present there are 183 people who have been arrested and charged with arson over the fires. Another cause has been green bans, poor land management and the ban on hazard reduction burning. People have to remember that Australia has always been a dry country and the Traditional Owners back burned and didn’t allow ground fuel build up like we have today. The worst problem is government inaction and slow in reacting to our current fire emergency with key politicians even taking overseas holidays while the country burns. The heroes of all this has been our firefighters and emergency services on the ground. A lot of the firefighters are volunteers who sadly have had very little support or resources from both federal or state governments with many forced to use their own vehicles, fuel and equipment and because of the size of the fires have been fighting them for months with very little rest.
